ational things that will be a better guarantee of steady pay.  It's a ***TOUGH*** balance to strike; a make or break quality that separates the Humberto Ramos' (notoriously consistent &amp; prolific artwork) from the Joe Madureira's (notoriously gorgeous art but VERY inconsistent)<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -(2) RESPONSIBILITY &amp; PERSONABILITY:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> If you are up-front &amp; responsible about what you can AND CAN'T do for your editors, AND can do it without being a complete jerk, you can be guaranteed a spot on an editor's cellphone list &amp; more likely for to be on call to do work for them for being such a pleasant &amp; dependable employee.  An editor probably won't like it, but they're respect you TEN TIMES more if you can tell them you CAN'T meet a deadline they set, instead of springing the &quot;surprise&quot; when the work is due.<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> -(3) QUALITY OF WORK &amp; AUDIENCE RESPONSE:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Flat out, if something's done every month on time, with care and attention by all workers, but people think it's ugly, more than likely they won't want to pay for it.  It's not to say we're all shallow (wait... we are!), but the better &amp; more pleasing the art is at least extra credit for the artist, and often times editors &amp; readers are willing to suffer someone's poor character &amp; work ethic just to have another month of their glorious artwork.<br>Style plays a SMALL part in this (I asked), as really a style is subjective &amp; can appeal to almost any one person, regardless of the popularity of the overall product or artist.<br>But if the art is just completely <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> beautiful</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->; contains a huge amount of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> refined technique, confidence in execution &amp; BEGS to be looked at</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> *that*</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is the key to winning audiences.<br><br>So, what do you all think?<br>Worthwhile advice or a load of who-hah?<br>Any of you got better advice?<br><br>-TBW <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usuperrats.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Super Rats</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/15/02 12:02:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3935.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.happysoda.com/images/eboardavbp.jpg height=130 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: 3 Important Things About Getting Published.</span><hr size=1> It really all boils down to #3.  #1 and #2 are essential for a career, but don't come into play (as far as getting paid) until #3 is satisfied, so those who are looking to get published should focus on #3...of course having a good work ethic (1) and being a considerate human being (2) do wonders for improving your art (3).  <p>=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=<br>If you ever want me to grope your chest, let me know.  It's better than letting that spider eat you up inside, don't you think?.<br><br><a href="http://www.happysoda.com"><img src="http://www.happysoda.com/banner.gif" border="1"></A></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showPrevMessage?topicID=3935.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showNextMessage?topicID=3935.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3935.topic&index=1><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign=